# Executive Summary

The strongest clue is the **consistent 1-in-6 failure rate**, which usually indicates **one backend out of six is unhealthy yet still receiving traffic**. Because there was **no application deployment** but a **host-project networking Terraform change** occurred earlier, I would prioritize **load balancer backend health, NEG membership, pod readiness, node-level networking, firewall rules, routes, network tags, and Cloud NAT** before investigating Cloud SQL. I would first determine whether the 5xx is generated by the load balancer or application, identify whether all failures map to the same pod/node/backend endpoint, and correlate that with the morning Terraform change. Immediate mitigation would be removing the bad endpoint, draining the affected node, or rolling back the networking change through emergency change control. The durable fix would include stronger readiness checks, networking validation tests in CI/CD, post-change monitoring, and alerts on 5xx rates and backend health degradation.
